<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-129-224 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 969 920</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computers in Healthcare  June 15 1991 v12 nSPEISS p24(6).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>An open, modular, distributed and redundant computer system forhospitals. (MUMPS Special Edition)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Schuller, Gunther.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A successful hospital information system must be able to supportareas of knowledge that change rapidly, be able to integrate allsources and users of data in the hospital, be on service 24 hoursa day, be extensible, and be flexible.andP;  The solution arrived at bythe teaching hospital at the University of Wurzburg in Germany isbased on parallel and distributed processing and uses theDecentralized Hospital Computer Program from the US Dept ofVeterans Affairs.andP;  IBM-compatible MS-DOS-based machines are used.andO;The MUMPS programming system is used because an applicationwritten in standard MUMPS can be ported easily from one machine toanother.andP;  The system consists of a pair of hospital informationservers, a MS-DOS loading server, and a gateway server tomainframe computers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Product:   Intel 80286 (Microprocessor) (Usage).andO;Topic:     MUMPSHospital Information SystemsOpen SystemsMS-DOSUnited States. Department of Veterans Affairs.andO;Feature:   illustrationtablechart.andO;Caption:   Requirements for HIS. (table)Multifunctional modes of use of a DCU. (chart)Overall basic software configuration. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>